                        </a></div></div><ol class="sense_single" htag="ol"><li class="sense" htag="li" id="adamant_sng_1" hclass="sense"><span class="sensetop" hclass="sensetop" htag="span"><span class="def" hclass="def" htag="span">determined not to change your mind or to be persuaded about something</span></span><ul class="examples" hclass="examples" htag="ul"><li class="" htag="li"><span class="x">Eva was adamant that she would not come.</span></li><li class="" htag="li"><span class="x">The government remained adamant that there was no more money available.</span></li></ul><div class="collapse" htag="div" hclass="collapse"><span class="unbox" unbox="snippet" id="adamant_unbox_1"><span class="box_title">Oxford Collocations Dictionary</span><span class="body"><span class="p"><span class="eb">Adamant</span> is used with these nouns: <ul class="collocs_list"><li class="li" bord="n">refusal</li></ul></span><span class="xref_to_full_entry">See <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/collocations/adamant" title=" definition in Collocations
 ">full entry</a></span></span></span></div><div class="collapse" htag="div" hclass="collapse"><span class="unbox" id="adamant_unbox_2" unbox="wordorigin"><span class="box_title">Word Origin</span><span class="body"><span class="p">Old English (as a noun), from Old French <span class="ei">adamaunt-</span>, via Latin from Greek <span class="ei">adamas</span>, <span class="ei">adamant-</span>, ‘untameable, invincible’ (later used to denote the hardest metal or stone, hence diamond), from <span class="ei">a-</span> ‘not’ + <span class="ei">daman</span> ‘to tame’.</span></span></span></div>    <div id="ring-links-box">
